      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was a synchronous but independent failure of multiple palace systems due to an internal social contradiction: the increasing extraction of surplus by a non-productive elite led to a demographic collapse as peasants fled the oppressive palatial control.\", \"mechanism\": \"The Linear B tablets show a micromanaging, extractive economy. Over centuries, this stifled rural resilience. A minor climatic fluctuation or external pressure triggered a mass abandonment of the countryside. Without farmers, the palaces starved. This happened independently in each region due to the same internal structural flaw. Egypt survived because its ideology (the Pharaoh as divine guarantor of cosmic order) and its system of regional nomarchs provided a more flexible and legitimate framework for tax collection and labor mobilization.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Archaeological surveys show a continuous, dense pattern of rural settlement in Mycenaean Greece right up to the destruction of the palaces.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Linear B tablets from Pylos show a sudden, emergency military conscription of coastal watchers, not a slow rural depopulation.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is a Marxist/social-contradiction counterexample. It argues the collapse was not a single event but a synchronous implosion of brittle, over-extractive systems. The simultaneity is explained by the similar structural evolution of the palace economies.\"}",
